[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"55fe4c0065a0892a40a712be0eccfe42bb4fa751","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46886 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_mlir_rocm_fix_210128

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Melon-Tropics/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.

0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False

The previous changes removing support for using the trailing positional
argument as a working directory missed a spot in the apply/destroy
command implementation. We still support this argument for applying a
saved plan:

    terraform apply foo.tfplan

However, if you pass a positional path which doesn't "look like" a plan
(for example, the path to a configuration directory), Terraform would
silently ignore it and continue.

This commit fixes that by adding an error message if the user specifies
a path which the plan loader rejects as not "looking like" a plan. This
message includes a reference to the `-chdir` flag as a pointer about
what to do next.

We also rearrange the error message when calling `terraform destroy`
with a plan file argument, and add test coverage for the above. While
we're here, update the destroy tests to copy the fixture directory,
chdir, and defer cleanup.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d7613a0aac1f42f9e05e9d9c3a3d9d53b554ddfa"}]

[{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"9816d1d0dc42f9ebb8d0390bb38a93f9cab0ca2b","author":{"name":"A. [{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

Sets up a cron trigger to publish prereleases at 16:00 UTC (11 am
Eastern, 8 am Pacific) on every weekday (Monday through Friday).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca"}]

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Change-Id: Ibad02cee524e744bb6ef7f50a52e4d27030ac4c0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/581a3825f85cb910890ec25983d22a68e0ec8dca"},{"sha":"a0bd36e7f47f1e0305d8577096e1660ca1c9aa4f","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Support passing and returning Nones in TPUStrategy.

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

[{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"47cda6685c908bedacee11002b66e989ccc70894","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd (#1419)

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

So I'm doing this.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/4c019585e875b4197519052604764652a1ccb06a"},{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"}]

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need

environment variable panel.

easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't

[{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"642c428a83be79750a8b640bfc06017b42d9616a","author":{"name":"Stephan Herhut","email":"008c77519b8a73e523165e08d16a53f89ff557b3@google.com"},"message":"Add kernel definition for zeta operation.

platforms.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

[{"sha":"ab3712d685ad3ab429d7f78c9daf094bcd2f5c97","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/ab3712d685ad3ab429d7f78c9daf094bcd2f5c97"}]

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"642c428a83be79750a8b640bfc06017b42d9616a","author":{"name":"Stephan Herhut","email":"008c77519b8a73e523165e08d16a53f89ff557b3@google.com"},"message":"Add kernel definition for zeta operation.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"55fe4c0065a0892a40a712be0eccfe42bb4fa751","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46886 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_mlir_rocm_fix_210128

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"5e4b8bd011ed3c175775b6c1c67ea7a367da8181","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday

Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kolyshkin/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kolyshkin/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kolyshkin/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

This switches the hcsshim dependency back to tagged releases, instead of the special
"moby" branch. This makes the dependency align with both BuildKit and containerd,
which use these versions.

The switch to the "moby" branch was done in 286547848751229fa14974da389e1d4c676d8ee5,
to bring in a fix for image import, without having to bring in additional changes;

> We changed to the moby branch for a couple of reasons:
>
> - Allows us to take this important change without needing to also pull in all
>   of the other work that has been going on in the repo.
> - moby uses an older set of APIs exposed from hcsshim, based on the HCS v1
>   functionality. Going forwards, we have discussed deprecating/removing these
>   APIs from the mainline branch in hcsshim, so our thinking was we could keep
>   this moby branch around to ensure we don't break compatibility there.
>
> (...) Long term, the best path here is to get moby using containerd as the
> backend on Windows, which should alleviate these issues.

full diff: https://github.com/Microsoft/hcsshim/compare/9dcb42f100215f8d375b4a9265e5bba009217a85..v0.8.10

Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in

participant.

everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"dc6baf66c1eb73d624c645b171a25058936765e2","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switch Dockerfile.rocm to use ROCm 4.0.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/dc6baf66c1eb73d624c645b171a25058936765e2"},{"sha":"b2e175a6e25f7fd173ab57aa8b845e76650110d1","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switch ROCm CI scripts to use ROCM 4.0.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/b2e175a6e25f7fd173ab57aa8b845e76650110d1"},{"sha":"42ca44080f25ef2d7b31399334097f1f15eb1fca","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Removing deprecated CI scripts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/42ca44080f25ef2d7b31399334097f1f15eb1fca"},{"sha":"6ff048e95114626b6b493af3c09ce831ed847ee6","author":{"name":"Chenkai Kuang","email":"7beef3d4abac50ba4f05b7c8a0ee8f7890e6f990@google.com"},"message":"Comment on why NCCL can't be ordered in tf1.
