[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

[{"sha":"942281fe1ff09e7b525cd400d1613822a8798801","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/942281fe1ff09e7b525cd400d1613822a8798801"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"dc6baf66c1eb73d624c645b171a25058936765e2","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switch Dockerfile.rocm to use ROCm 4.0.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/dc6baf66c1eb73d624c645b171a25058936765e2"},{"sha":"b2e175a6e25f7fd173ab57aa8b845e76650110d1","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switch ROCm CI scripts to use ROCM 4.0.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/b2e175a6e25f7fd173ab57aa8b845e76650110d1"},{"sha":"42ca44080f25ef2d7b31399334097f1f15eb1fca","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Removing deprecated CI scripts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/42ca44080f25ef2d7b31399334097f1f15eb1fca"},{"sha":"6ff048e95114626b6b493af3c09ce831ed847ee6","author":{"name":"Chenkai Kuang","email":"7beef3d4abac50ba4f05b7c8a0ee8f7890e6f990@google.com"},"message":"Comment on why NCCL can't be ordered in tf1.

[{"sha":"10f7e2f6f7014e42c19f2f9ebd7b3cbf586b3f13","author":{"name":"Kristin Laemmert","email":"30cb4a936f196f8da41f6469d07b31397d334edc@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"configs/configschema: add an inner Object specific to a NestedType

My original plans to use Blocks inside NestedTypes did not work out due
to some important behavioral differences between blocks and attributes
(encounted in the plans/objchange package, which will be updated in the
next commit).

This commit adds a new type, Object, which replaces the Block inside an
attributes NestedType, and updated the related decoderSpec function to
handle the new type. I've also added an ImpliedType() function specific
to Objects.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/10f7e2f6f7014e42c19f2f9ebd7b3cbf586b3f13"},{"sha":"1706db590ce9281aec2ec616a345445eda4ca68b","author":{"name":"Kristin Laemmert","email":"30cb4a936f196f8da41f6469d07b31397d334edc@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"plans/objchange: rename ProposedNewObject to ProposedNew

Now that there is an actual configschema.Object it will be clearer if
the function names match the type the act upon. The next commit will
introduce a new version of proposedNewObject which takes a
configschema.Object.

The objchange tests fail in this commit, but that is deliberate for the
sake of small, easily readable commits. The next commit (which adds
proposedNewObject) will fix those test failures.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/1706db590ce9281aec2ec616a345445eda4ca68b"},{"sha":"b291667e12d5dce7e0d88ba6d1db44cf449b1fb3","author":{"name":"Kristin Laemmert","email":"30cb4a936f196f8da41f6469d07b31397d334edc@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"plans/objchange: extend assertPlannedValueValid to handle attributes

NestedTypes inside attributes. It is very similar to the handling of
blocks in assertPlanValid. The main difference is that a null NestedType
is valid (either planned or in config).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b291667e12d5dce7e0d88ba6d1db44cf449b1fb3"}]

[{"sha":"00e38c80b28fd9b5e99b890d85e080edc2fcc49f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fallback if GitHub status is stuck as "pending" (#20729)

GitHub's status API is super flaky. Sometimes it reports a job as
"pending" even after it completes in CircleCI. If it's still pending
when we time out, return the build ID anyway. TODO: The location of the

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

everywhere it may be accessed.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"db5945efee7cffae0a4d6c9fa4e08deec2f49e40","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Set default release channel for download-experimental-build script (#20663)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/db5945efee7cffae0a4d6c9fa4e08deec2f49e40"},{"sha":"d13f5b9538e48f74f7c571ef3cde652ca887cca0","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Experiment: Unsuspend all lanes on update (#20660)

Adds a feature flag to tweak the internal heuristic used to "unsuspend"
lanes when a new update comes in.

A lane is "suspended" if we couldn't finish rendering it because it was
missing data, and we chose not to commit the fallback. (In this context,
"suspended" does not include updates that finished with a fallback.)

When we receive new data in the form of an update, we need to retry
rendering the suspended lanes, since the new data may have unblocked the
previously suspended work. For example, the new update could navigate
back to an already loaded route.

It's impractical to retry every combination of suspended lanes, so we
need some heuristic that decides which lanes to retry and in
which order.

The existing heuristic roughly approximates the old Expiration Times
model. It unsuspends all lower priority lanes, but leaves higher
priority lanes suspended.

Then when we start rendering, we choose the lanes that have the highest
LanePriority and render those -- and then we add to that all the lanes
that are highher priority.

If this sounds terribly confusing, it's because it barely makes sense.
(It made more sense in the Expiration Times world, I promise, but it
was still confusing.) I don't think it's worth me trying to explain the
old behavior too much because the point here is that we can replace it
with something simpler.

The new heurstic is to unsuspend all suspended lanes whenever there's
an update.

This is effectively what we already do except in a few very specific
edge cases, ever since we removed the delayed suspense feature from
everything that's not a refresh transition.

We can optimize this in the future to only unsuspend lanes that are
either 1) in the `lanes` or `subtreeLanes` of the node that was updated,
or 2) in the `lanes` of the return path of the node that was updated.
This would exclude lanes that are only located in unrelated sibling
trees. But, this optimization wouldn't be useful currently because we
assign the same transition lane to all transitions. It will become
relevant again once we start assigning arbitrary lanes to transitions
-- but that in turn requires us to implement entanglement of overlapping
transitions, one of our planned projects.

So to sum up: the goal here is to remove the weird edge cases and switch
to a simpler model, on top of which we can make more substantial
improvements.

I put it behind a flag so I can run an A/B test and confirm it doesn't
cause a regression.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/d13f5b9538e48f74f7c571ef3cde652ca887cca0"},{"sha":"9c32622cf04e70dd40463ece25e83b7cc311b0ed","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Improve tests that use discrete events (#20667)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/9c32622cf04e70dd40463ece25e83b7cc311b0ed"},{"sha":"e316f785526e503eceed1ae33b7a06440084b9c9","author":{"name":"Joshua Gross","email":"d29bc49d09431027501fa5b225ec1424670862ff@gmail.com"},"message":"RN: Implement `sendAccessibilityEvent` in RN Renderer that proxies between Fabric/non-Fabric (#20554)

When multiple transitions update the same queue, only the most recent
one should be allowed to finish. We shouldn't show intermediate states.

See #17418 for background on why this is important.

The way this currently works is that we always assign the same lane to
all transitions. It's impossible for one transition to finish without
also finishing all the others.

The downside of the current approach is that it's too aggressive. Not
all transitions are related to each other, so one should not block
the other.

The new approach is to only entangle transitions if they update one or
more of the same state hooks (or class components), because this
indicates that they are related. If they are unrelated, then they can
finish in any order, as long as they have different lanes.

However, this commit does not change anything about how the lanes are
assigned. All it does is add the mechanism to entangle per queue. So it
doesn't actually change any behavior, yet. But it's a requirement for my
next step, which is to assign different lanes to consecutive transitions
until we run out and cycle back to the beginning.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/deeeaf1d222ba29bcce6eda0a1c4423ce10e727a"},{"sha":"aa736a0fa6e22f902bd7a98dcb9b24d8c4310e35","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add queue microtask to host configs (#20668)

* Concurrent Mode test for uMS render mutation

Same test as the one added in #20665, but for Concurrent Mode.

* Use double render to detect render phase mutation

PR #20665 added a mechanism to detect when a `useMutableSource` source
is mutated during the render phase. It relies on the fact that we double
invoke components that error during development using
`invokeGuardedCallback`. If the version in the double render doesn't
match the first, that indicates there must have been a mutation during
render.

At first I thought it worked by detecting inside the *other* double
render, the one we do for Strict Mode. It turns out that while it does
warn then, the warning is suppressed, because we suppress all console
methods that occur during the Strict Mode double render. So it's really
the `invokeGuardedCallback` one that makes it work.

Anyway, let's set that aside that issue for a second. I realized during
review that errors that occur during the Strict Mode double render
reveal a useful property: A pure component will never throw during the
double render, because if it were pure, it would have also thrown during
the first render... in which case it wouldn't have double rendered! This
is true of all such errors, not just the one thrown by
`useMutableSource`.

Given this, we can simplify the `useMutableSource` mutation detection
mechanism. Instead of tracking and comparing the source's version, we
can instead check if we're inside a double render when the error is
thrown.

To get around the console suppression issue, I changed the warning to an
error. It errors regardless, in both dev and prod, so it doesn't have
semantic implications.

However, because of the paradox I described above, we arguably
_shouldn't_ throw an error in development, since we know that error
won't happen in production, because prod doesn't double render. (It's
still a tearing bug, but that doesn't mean the component will actually
throw.) I considered that, but that requires a larger conversation about
how to handle errors that we know are only possible in development. I
think we should probably be suppressing *all* errors (with a warning)
that occur during a double render.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/dc27b5aaae5e1a028dc77412d5396466aaa87268"},{"sha":"7cb9fd7ef822436aef13c8cbf648af1e21a5309a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land interleaved updates change in main fork (#20710)

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

Change-Id: I82622536fd89ce77993bcfe1c65f5f172e8ebcd4","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ddavis-2015/tensorflow/commits/37d51318b0680d99970790ccd1bb42454acbf2bb"},{"sha":"ea46ce224f29eea984ca04c6362b2d36d039565c","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Fix //tensorflow/core/common_runtime/eager:custom_device_test on Windows

The test on Windows needs an extra dependency on variable ops. Without an explicit dependency it seems like the ops themselves aren't registered, but based on logged errors the kernels try to register anyway.

It shouldn't be possible to get kernels without ops. This could be related to the is_external flag on tf_gen_op_lib which affects Windows linking. But it's a bit more complicated than I can figure out by trial and error on an extremely long presubmit.

Otherwise `experimental_implements` and `experimental_follow_type_hints` are broken if user tries to instantiate get_concrete_function with TensorSpec (e.g. https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/pull/2344#issuecomment-762132670)

2) While refactoring for (1) fixed small bug in convert_annotated_args_to_tensors, where keyword arguments were not converted if both of the following were true  a) **kwargs is not present and b) the argument passed by keyword, but is not kwonly (e.g.standard arguement, before *). For example

```
@tf.function(experimental_follow_type_hints=True)
def foo(x:tf.Tensor, y): return x + y

foo(x=1, y=1)
foo(x=2, y=1)  # should not retrace!
```

it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in

participant.

everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"e5de65fba602d58ee838d87b92896a9178baec85","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add ability to have format specifiers with DebugLog.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of DebugLog
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use of the
        DebugLog (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either DebugLog or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call DebugLog(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/e5de65fba602d58ee838d87b92896a9178baec85"}]

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"6be1ebb8498e2ccdb5d05ad673678b98a9373346","author":{"name":"Jaehong Kim","email":"110b51579386d0730c935f562141060df20aac1e@google.com"},"message":"Add nested function nodes checking logic for QAT validator.

Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355556020
Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"db5945efee7cffae0a4d6c9fa4e08deec2f49e40","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Set default release channel for download-experimental-build script (#20663)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/db5945efee7cffae0a4d6c9fa4e08deec2f49e40"},{"sha":"d13f5b9538e48f74f7c571ef3cde652ca887cca0","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Experiment: Unsuspend all lanes on update (#20660)

Adds a feature flag to tweak the internal heuristic used to "unsuspend"
lanes when a new update comes in.

A lane is "suspended" if we couldn't finish rendering it because it was
missing data, and we chose not to commit the fallback. (In this context,
"suspended" does not include updates that finished with a fallback.)

When we receive new data in the form of an update, we need to retry
rendering the suspended lanes, since the new data may have unblocked the
previously suspended work. For example, the new update could navigate
back to an already loaded route.

It's impractical to retry every combination of suspended lanes, so we
need some heuristic that decides which lanes to retry and in
which order.

The existing heuristic roughly approximates the old Expiration Times
model. It unsuspends all lower priority lanes, but leaves higher
priority lanes suspended.

Then when we start rendering, we choose the lanes that have the highest
LanePriority and render those -- and then we add to that all the lanes
that are highher priority.

If this sounds terribly confusing, it's because it barely makes sense.
(It made more sense in the Expiration Times world, I promise, but it
was still confusing.) I don't think it's worth me trying to explain the
old behavior too much because the point here is that we can replace it
with something simpler.

The new heurstic is to unsuspend all suspended lanes whenever there's
an update.

This is effectively what we already do except in a few very specific
edge cases, ever since we removed the delayed suspense feature from
everything that's not a refresh transition.

We can optimize this in the future to only unsuspend lanes that are
either 1) in the `lanes` or `subtreeLanes` of the node that was updated,
or 2) in the `lanes` of the return path of the node that was updated.
This would exclude lanes that are only located in unrelated sibling
trees. But, this optimization wouldn't be useful currently because we
assign the same transition lane to all transitions. It will become
relevant again once we start assigning arbitrary lanes to transitions
-- but that in turn requires us to implement entanglement of overlapping
transitions, one of our planned projects.

So to sum up: the goal here is to remove the weird edge cases and switch
to a simpler model, on top of which we can make more substantial
improvements.

I put it behind a flag so I can run an A/B test and confirm it doesn't
cause a regression.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/d13f5b9538e48f74f7c571ef3cde652ca887cca0"},{"sha":"9c32622cf04e70dd40463ece25e83b7cc311b0ed","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Improve tests that use discrete events (#20667)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/9c32622cf04e70dd40463ece25e83b7cc311b0ed"},{"sha":"e316f785526e503eceed1ae33b7a06440084b9c9","author":{"name":"Joshua Gross","email":"d29bc49d09431027501fa5b225ec1424670862ff@gmail.com"},"message":"RN: Implement `sendAccessibilityEvent` in RN Renderer that proxies between Fabric/non-Fabric (#20554)

* prettier","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/e316f785526e503eceed1ae33b7a06440084b9c9"},{"sha":"deeeaf1d222ba29bcce6eda0a1c4423ce10e727a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Entangle overlapping transitions per queue (#20670)

When multiple transitions update the same queue, only the most recent
one should be allowed to finish. We shouldn't show intermediate states.

See #17418 for background on why this is important.

The way this currently works is that we always assign the same lane to
all transitions. It's impossible for one transition to finish without
also finishing all the others.

The downside of the current approach is that it's too aggressive. Not
all transitions are related to each other, so one should not block
the other.

The new approach is to only entangle transitions if they update one or
more of the same state hooks (or class components), because this
indicates that they are related. If they are unrelated, then they can
finish in any order, as long as they have different lanes.

However, this commit does not change anything about how the lanes are
assigned. All it does is add the mechanism to entangle per queue. So it
doesn't actually change any behavior, yet. But it's a requirement for my
next step, which is to assign different lanes to consecutive transitions
until we run out and cycle back to the beginning.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/deeeaf1d222ba29bcce6eda0a1c4423ce10e727a"},{"sha":"aa736a0fa6e22f902bd7a98dcb9b24d8c4310e35","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add queue microtask to host configs (#20668)

The memoized state of effect hooks is only invalidated when deps change. Deps are compared between the previous effect and the current effect. This can be problematic if one commit consists of an update that has changed deps followed by an update that has equal deps. That commit will lead to memoizedState containing the changed deps even though we committed with unchanged deps.

The n+1 update will therefore run an effect because we compare the updated deps with the deps with which we never actually committed.

To prevent this we now invalidate memoizedState on every updateEffectImpl call so that memoizedStat.deps always points to the latest deps.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/bb1b7951d182d36345c83154f9d9bab218011b46"},{"sha":"f8b6969da65457cd18b434616cb01ac1c7b0afcc","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Add `--commit` param to release scripts (#20703)

* Concurrent Mode test for uMS render mutation

Same test as the one added in #20665, but for Concurrent Mode.

* Use double render to detect render phase mutation

PR #20665 added a mechanism to detect when a `useMutableSource` source
is mutated during the render phase. It relies on the fact that we double
invoke components that error during development using
`invokeGuardedCallback`. If the version in the double render doesn't
match the first, that indicates there must have been a mutation during
render.

At first I thought it worked by detecting inside the *other* double
render, the one we do for Strict Mode. It turns out that while it does
warn then, the warning is suppressed, because we suppress all console
methods that occur during the Strict Mode double render. So it's really
the `invokeGuardedCallback` one that makes it work.

Anyway, let's set that aside that issue for a second. I realized during
review that errors that occur during the Strict Mode double render
reveal a useful property: A pure component will never throw during the
double render, because if it were pure, it would have also thrown during
the first render... in which case it wouldn't have double rendered! This
is true of all such errors, not just the one thrown by
`useMutableSource`.

Given this, we can simplify the `useMutableSource` mutation detection
mechanism. Instead of tracking and comparing the source's version, we
can instead check if we're inside a double render when the error is
thrown.

To get around the console suppression issue, I changed the warning to an
error. It errors regardless, in both dev and prod, so it doesn't have
semantic implications.

However, because of the paradox I described above, we arguably
_shouldn't_ throw an error in development, since we know that error
won't happen in production, because prod doesn't double render. (It's
still a tearing bug, but that doesn't mean the component will actually
throw.) I considered that, but that requires a larger conversation about
how to handle errors that we know are only possible in development. I
think we should probably be suppressing *all* errors (with a warning)
that occur during a double render.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iChenLei/react/commits/dc27b5aaae5e1a028dc77412d5396466aaa87268"},{"sha":"7cb9fd7ef822436aef13c8cbf648af1e21a5309a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Land interleaved updates change in main fork (#20710)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pjbgf/moby/commits/66dffbec86dbea1b04180699106d5b8a73d5424b"},{"sha":"4b5aa28f2466308acab98fc35586723492347fc5","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Do not set DOCKER_TMP to be owned by remapped root

The remapped root does not need access to this dir.
Having this owned by the remapped root opens the host up to an
uprivileged user on the host being able to escalate privileges.

While it would not be normal for the remapped UID to be used outside of
the container context, it could happen.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit bfedd2725971303efb7a2fe5d6990317b381622f)
Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pjbgf/moby/commits/4b5aa28f2466308acab98fc35586723492347fc5"},{"sha":"7f5e39bd4f92ce6fcf9946aa8ccea91815c321c2","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Use real root with 0701 perms

Various dirs in /var/lib/docker contain data that needs to be mounted
into a container. For this reason, these dirs are set to be owned by the
remapped root user, otherwise there can be permissions issues.
However, this uneccessarily exposes these dirs to an unprivileged user
on the host.

Instead, set the ownership of these dirs to the real root (or rather the
UID/GID of dockerd) with 0701 permissions, which allows the remapped
root to enter the directories but not read/write to them.
The remapped root needs to enter these dirs so the container's rootfs
can be configured... e.g. to mount /etc/resolve.conf.

This prevents an unprivileged user from having read/write access to
these dirs on the host.
The flip side of this is now any user can enter these directories.

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs
