Change-Id: I5e8a91615186098f596269bed11c151c70eb5020","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/e743fcee33f61ee2b23b72235afc388cef7161bb"},{"sha":"18eaf4e8f1769d2bb05ed354a8b6198e49aadfcc","author":{"name":"Ayush Dubey","email":"a9c32da01a297903962aa453bd3cb6e8c13c2563@google.com"},"message":"Ensure that `CollectiveParams` outlives all references to it.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

So I'm doing this.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/4c019585e875b4197519052604764652a1ccb06a"},{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

Sets up a cron trigger to publish prereleases at 16:00 UTC (11 am

Change-Id: I5e8a91615186098f596269bed11c151c70eb5020","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/e743fcee33f61ee2b23b72235afc388cef7161bb"},{"sha":"18eaf4e8f1769d2bb05ed354a8b6198e49aadfcc","author":{"name":"Ayush Dubey","email":"a9c32da01a297903962aa453bd3cb6e8c13c2563@google.com"},"message":"Ensure that `CollectiveParams` outlives all references to it.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

Change-Id: I5e8a91615186098f596269bed11c151c70eb5020","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/e743fcee33f61ee2b23b72235afc388cef7161bb"},{"sha":"18eaf4e8f1769d2bb05ed354a8b6198e49aadfcc","author":{"name":"Ayush Dubey","email":"a9c32da01a297903962aa453bd3cb6e8c13c2563@google.com"},"message":"Ensure that `CollectiveParams` outlives all references to it.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"}]

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. [{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"3d88e66c1404287c708c74ba02953966e83d2841","author":{"name":"Meghna Natraj","email":"2565af4be4b9e3f79d7ed44b02ee9244f1214104@google.com"},"message":"Replace python I/O with TF I/O APIs

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/8df35fb50140606945ca1e207c676c2f605adebc"}]

Change-Id: I4afa0b7d657fedf2ef5355e5065eb82b8a7f4b74","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bytedance/tensorflow/commits/473d70ed4ee455b41bbbc74f71bf094411bcf783"},{"sha":"0fa8e3c7ddfd449e6a4af84925f63be2401e0a30","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Introduce legacy quantization mode in MLIR quantizer

The "Legacy mode" is for checking if the MLIR quantizer can output the exactly
same values with TOCO quantizer. When enabled, quantization logics are changed
to calculate scales in single-precision float, rather than default
double-precision. This makes scales exactly same for both quantizer outputs,
so that the buffers can be quantized to the same values. When double-precision
scale is used, although it might result in smaller error at the end, it's hard
to verify one-off errors in quantized values are from actual bug or slight
difference in scale.

Specifically, these values are forced to be calculated in `float`.
* Calibrated ranges. ((float)max - (float)min) / range is used.
* Bias scales. Multiplied value is downcasted to float.

Also,  quantization calls TOCO's quantization logic. TOCO quantized values with reciprocal scale (1/scale). This ensures the quantized values are the same when MLIR quantizer converted the model to correct graph and scales.

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"55fe4c0065a0892a40a712be0eccfe42bb4fa751","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46886 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_mlir_rocm_fix_210128

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"55fe4c0065a0892a40a712be0eccfe42bb4fa751","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46886 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_mlir_rocm_fix_210128

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

Sets up a cron trigger to publish prereleases at 16:00 UTC (11 am

The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

[{"sha":"9b859df1da0bd3531009c66ec85ab471a2a04202","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/9b859df1da0bd3531009c66ec85ab471a2a04202"}]

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"ad8a2e8b918ebbc0ca610b8e7445955bab74b306","author":{"name":"Brian Flad","email":"2d9d7b80898d9ce2184cfa69cb628eece272cafc@gmail.com"},"message":"deps: Bump github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go@v1.37.0

Changes:

```
* backend/s3: Support for AWS Single-Sign On (SSO) cached credentials
```

Updated via:

```
go get github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go@v1.37.0
go mod tidy
```

Please note that Terraform CLI will not initiate or perform the AWS SSO login flow. It is expected that you have already performed the SSO login flow using AWS CLI using the `aws sso login` command, or by some other mechanism before executing Terraform. More precisely, this credential handling must find a valid non-expired access token for the AWS SSO user portal URL in `~/.aws/sso/cache`. If a cached token is not found, is expired, or the file is malformed an error will be returned.

You can use configure AWS SSO credentials from the AWS shared configuration file by specifying the required keys in the profile:

```
sso_account_id
sso_region
sso_role_name
sso_start_url
```

For example, the following defines a profile "devsso" and specifies the AWS SSO parameters that defines the target account, role, sign-on portal, and the region where the user portal is located. Note: all SSO arguments must be provided, or an error will be returned.

```
[profile devsso]
sso_start_url = https:my-sso-portal.awsapps.com/start
sso_role_name = SSOReadOnlyRole
sso_region = us-east-1
sso_account_id = 123456789012
```

Additional Resources

* [Configuring the AWS CLI to use AWS Single Sign-On](https:docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/cli-configure-sso.html)

argument to specify a working directory. This functionality has been
replaced with the global -chdir flag, which is specified before any
other arguments, including the sub-command name.

This commit removes support for the trailing path parameter from
most commands. The only command which still supports a path argument is
fmt, which also supports "-" to indicate receiving configuration from
standard input.

Any invocation of a command with an invalid trailing path parameter will
result in a short error message, pointing at the -chdir alternative.

There are many test updates in this commit, almost all of which are
migrations from using positional arguments to specify a working
directory. Because of the layer at which these tests run, we are unable
to use the -chdir argument, so the churn in test files is larger than
ideal. [{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

[{"sha":"a0bd36e7f47f1e0305d8577096e1660ca1c9aa4f","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Support passing and returning Nones in TPUStrategy.

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

Changes:

```
* backend/s3: Support for AWS Single-Sign On (SSO) cached credentials
```

Updated via:

```
go get github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go@v1.37.0
go mod tidy
```

Please note that Terraform CLI will not initiate or perform the AWS SSO login flow. It is expected that you have already performed the SSO login flow using AWS CLI using the `aws sso login` command, or by some other mechanism before executing Terraform. More precisely, this credential handling must find a valid non-expired access token for the AWS SSO user portal URL in `~/.aws/sso/cache`. If a cached token is not found, is expired, or the file is malformed an error will be returned.

You can use configure AWS SSO credentials from the AWS shared configuration file by specifying the required keys in the profile:

```
sso_account_id
sso_region
sso_role_name
sso_start_url
```

For example, the following defines a profile "devsso" and specifies the AWS SSO parameters that defines the target account, role, sign-on portal, and the region where the user portal is located. Note: all SSO arguments must be provided, or an error will be returned.

```
[profile devsso]
sso_start_url = https:my-sso-portal.awsapps.com/start
sso_role_name = SSOReadOnlyRole
sso_region = us-east-1
sso_account_id = 123456789012
```

Additional Resources

* [Configuring the AWS CLI to use AWS Single Sign-On](https:docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/cli-configure-sso.html)

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,

[{"sha":"5cc1753f2c9a52dd7f943f874d96cbdbc81aa542","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Fix daemon panic when starting container with invalid device cgroup rule

This fixes a panic when an invalid "device cgroup rule" is passed, resulting
in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

everywhere it may be accessed.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"dc6baf66c1eb73d624c645b171a25058936765e2","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switch Dockerfile.rocm to use ROCm 4.0.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/dc6baf66c1eb73d624c645b171a25058936765e2"},{"sha":"b2e175a6e25f7fd173ab57aa8b845e76650110d1","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Switch ROCm CI scripts to use ROCM 4.0.1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/b2e175a6e25f7fd173ab57aa8b845e76650110d1"},{"sha":"42ca44080f25ef2d7b31399334097f1f15eb1fca","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Removing deprecated CI scripts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/42ca44080f25ef2d7b31399334097f1f15eb1fca"},{"sha":"952fe2581d66444f611f62066afbdb4adefb3f9a","author":{"name":"Mahesh Ravishankar","email":"250c01e19e0e0b9b4e89cd38b383d403c45ab644@google.com"},"message":"Use linalg.fill on tensors instead of tensor.generate in MHLO -> Linalg conversion.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"}]

etcd rewrote its import path from coreos/etcd to go.etcd.io/etcd.
Changed the imports path in this commit, which also updates the code
version.

This lets us remove the github.com/ugorji/go/codec dependency, which
was pinned to a fairly old version. The net change is a loss of 30,000
lines of code in the vendor directory. (I first noticed this problem
because the outdated go/codec dependency was causing a dependency
failure when I tried to put Terraform and another project in the same
vendor directory.)

Note the version shows up funkily in go.mod, but I verified
visually it's the same commit as the "release-3.4" tag in
github.com/coreos/etcd. The etcd team plans to fix the release version
tagging in v3.5, which should be released soon.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kevinburkemeter/terraform/commits/310f3df4df7ca95701407fc74a7716ccb511cdeb"}]

[{"sha":"492b5d5987aee7f45a79ea9310d6b70332da0626","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

participant.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Disable Eigen docs builds by default.

Eigen documentation builds compile tools with the host toolchain which
it then tries to execute. When cross compiling doc tool execution
fails as the tools are built with the target toolchain. This change
disables Eigen docs builds by default to facilitate cross compilation.
Unfortunately, CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING can't be used to enable docs
builds when cross compilation is disabled as it does not work on Apple
platforms.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

[{"sha":"18eaf4e8f1769d2bb05ed354a8b6198e49aadfcc","author":{"name":"Ayush Dubey","email":"a9c32da01a297903962aa453bd3cb6e8c13c2563@google.com"},"message":"Ensure that `CollectiveParams` outlives all references to it.

Before this change, it was possible to access a `const CollectiveParams&` after
it was destroyed.  For example, the call to `UnblockDependencies` in
`NcclCommunicator::Enqueue` raced with the done_callback of the collective
participant.

This change makes `CollectiveParams` a refcounted object, and holds references
everywhere it may be accessed.

[{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

[{"sha":"c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Implement CI job that publishes prereleases (#20732)

PR #20728 added a command to initiate a prerelease using CI, but it left
the publish job unimplemented. This fills in the publish job.

Uses an npm automation token for authorization, which bypasses the need
for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

It does not yet support publishing arbitrary commits, though we could
easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

Always publishing from main is nice because it further incentivizes us
to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
merge broken PRs, we're fine.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/c64d6d21be19e179bd6a2d659fa78180051b577f"},{"sha":"f58ad2ad8ed2c38a111e1ab89d9f74fc925640ca","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Auto-publish prereleases every weekday (#20733)

[{"sha":"f8c0ebd4b4d36fcf8eb4ccb5c59e27aa4eb6971e","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add ability to have format specifiers with DebugLog.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of DebugLog
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use of the
        DebugLog (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either DebugLog or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call DebugLog(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/f8c0ebd4b4d36fcf8eb4ccb5c59e27aa4eb6971e"}]

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

In the meantime (i.e. until the TF LLVM commit pointer is updated to point to a commit that includes Jack's fix), we need to workaround this on the TF side, by adding a pass that converts the `fptosi f16 to i1` op to `fptosi f16 to i16` + `trunci i16 to i1`, which is what this commit does.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/41e8c71efb7efdb55fe83eab1bfde55b3a46bad4"},{"sha":"55fe4c0065a0892a40a712be0eccfe42bb4fa751","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46886 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_mlir_rocm_fix_210128

for a one-time password. The token is configured via CircleCI's
environment variable panel.

Currently, it will always publish the head of the main branch. If the
head has already been published, it will exit gracefully.

easily add that. I don't know how important that use case is, because
for PR branches, you can use CodeSandbox CI instead. Or as a last
resort, run the publish script locally.

to keep main in a releasable state. It also takes the guesswork out of
publishing a prerelease that's in a broken state: as long as we don't
